\title[The Euler problem of two fixed centers]{The Conley-Zehnder indices of the Euler problem of two fixed centers}



\author{Seongchan Kim}
 \address{Universit\"at Augsburg, Universit\"atsstrasse 14, D-86159 Augsburg, Germany}
 \email {seongchan.kim@math.uni-augsburg.de}












\begin{abstract}
We give explicit formulas of the Conley-Zehnder indices of the interior and exterior collision orbits and determine the Conley-Zehnder indices of all periodic orbits for energies below the critical Jacobi energy.  As a result,  we show that the universal cover of the regularized energy hypersurface of the Euler problem  is dynamically convex for energies below the critical Jacobi energy, and in that cover the lift of the doubly-covered exterior collision orbit is the unique periodic orbit of Conley-Zehnder index 3.
\end{abstract}



\maketitle



\section{Introduction}


The Euler problem of two fixed centers describes the motion of a massless body  under the influence of two fixed massive bodies according to Newton's law of gravitation. The two primaries will be referred to as the Earth and the Moon and  the massless body as  the satellite. The problem  was first introduced by Euler in 1760 and he considered this problem as a starting point to study the restricted three body problem \cite{Euler1}, \cite{Euler2}. Indeed, it can be obtained from the circular planar restricted three body problem. More precisely, the Euler problem  arises if we switch off the rotating term.  In 1902  Charlier  classified all orbits of this problem. He divided orbits into several classes according to the values of integrals, see \cite{Charlier}.  Pauli \cite{Pauli}   studied this problem to investigate the hydrogen molecular ion ${H_2^+}$. In such a situation, the two primaries are regarded as two protons and the massless body as an electron.  An interesting feature of the Euler  problem is the fact that the system is not rotationally invariant. In other words, when we switch on the second primary  in the Kepler problem, then angular momentum is not an integral any more (cf. Sec. \ref{subsection:integral}). However, this problem is still completely integrable which was first discovered by Euler. There are  distinguished periodic orbit, i.e., the interior collision orbit, the exterior collision orbit, the double collision orbit, the hyperbolic orbit, and the elliptic orbit. They are critical orbits, in other words, the derivatives of the Hamiltonian and the first integral are linearly dependent along these orbits and hence the corresponding leaf of the Liouville foliation is singular. They play  crucial roles in our argument.

\;\;

In the Euler problem, there are three distinguished energy levels that we denote by $c_J < c_1 < c_2$ at which the Liouville foliation changes. The energy level $c_J$, which  we call the critical Jacobi energy, is the unique critical value of the  Hamiltonian of the Euler problem. For  energies below this energy, the Hill's region consists of two bounded connected components, where each component is a neighborhood of one of the primaries. In such a situation, the satellite stays either close to the Earth or close to the Moon. Above the critical energy, the two connected components become connected, namely the satellite can move from near one    primary to near  the other primary. Each  connected component is noncompact due to collision of the satellite with one of the massive bodies. However, two body collisions can be regularized and hence the connected components can be compacified.  

\;\;

In this article, we recall the classification of the orbits and determine the Conley-Zehnder indices of all periodic orbits for  energies  below the critical Jacobi energy in the regularized system.   Here, the Conley-Zehnder index is the one introduced by Hofer-Wysocki-Zehnder \cite{HWZ}, which coincides with the transversal Conley-Zehnder index if a periodic orbit is nondegenerate. Introducing the elliptic coordinates $(\xi, \eta)$, one can compute the periods ${\tau_{\xi}}$ and $\tau_{\eta}$ of $\xi$- and $\eta$-oscillations of each periodic orbit. By the rotation number of a periodic orbit, we mean the ratio $R=\tau_{\eta}/\tau_{\xi}$. Our main result is the following.

\begin{Theorem}
\label{thm:formula} Assume that an energy is less than the critical Jacobi energy, i.e., $c<c_J$.  Then  the $N$-th iteration of the interior collision orbit  is    nondegenerate if and only if the product of the iteration number and the rotation number is not an integer, i.e., $NR_{\text{int}} \notin {\mathbb Z}$. For a nondegenerate orbit, the Conley-Zehnder index is given by

nexttext:

\;\;

Every regular orbit, i.e., the $T_{k,l}$-type orbit, is of Conley-Zehnder index $2k-1$.

\end{Theorem}



As a corollary of Theorem \ref{thm:formula}, we obtain the following theorem,  which is an analog of Theorem 1.1 of \cite{RKP} for the rotating Kepler problem.

\begin{Theorem}
\label{thm:index}
For energies below the critical Jacobi energy, the universal cover of the regularized energy hypersurface is dynamically convex, namely all  periodic Reeb orbits  have Conley-Zehnder indices at least 3. Moreover,  the doubly-covered exterior collision orbits are the unique periodic orbits of  Conley-Zehnder index 3 on each connected component.
\end{Theorem}

\begin{Remark} \rm We remark that the roles of the interior and the exterior collision orbits are reminiscent respectively of the roles of the direct and the retrograde circular orbits in the rotating Kepler problem, see \cite{RKP}.
\end{Remark}






\begin{Remark} \rm  The proofs of the following facts are analogous to those of the results for the restricted three body problem \cite{contact} (it is actually much simpler):


\;

(i) For $c<c_J$, each connected component of the energy hypersurface can be regularized to form the three-dimensional manifold which is diffeomorphic to ${\mathbb R} P^3 $. The two connected components of the regularized energy hypersurface are fiberwise star-shaped, where the explicit Liouville vector fields, which are transverse to the energy hypersurface, are of the form
\begin{eqnarray*}
X_E = (q-E) \frac{\partial }{ \partial q}, \;\;\;\;\; X_M = (q-M)\frac{\partial}{\partial q} .
\end{eqnarray*}
The contact structure on the regularized energy hypersurface  is isomorphic to the standard contact structure on ${\mathbb R} P^3$.

\;

(ii) There exists  ${\epsilon >0}$ and a Liouville vector field ${X}$ such that for $c_J < c < c_J + \epsilon$, ${X}$ is transverse to the energy hypersurface and coincides with $X_E$ and $X_M$ near $E$ and $M$, respectively. The regularized energy hypersurface is contactomorphic to $({\mathbb R} P^3, \xi_1) \sharp ({\mathbb R} P^3, \xi_2) $, where $\xi_1$ and $\xi_2$ are standard contact structures on ${\mathbb R} P^3$. In particular, the  connected sum is a contact connected sum. 
\end{Remark} 










