Notice that the physical transformation  $ (q,p) \mapsto ( \frac{q}{\sqrt{-2c}} , \sqrt{-2c} p )$ is a symplectomorphism. It follows that the regularized Kepler flow for any negative energy can be regarded as a geodesic flow on $S^2$ and an energy hypersurface is diffeomorphic to the unit cotangent bundle of ${ S^2}$. 








\subsection{Integrals of the Kepler problem}
\label{subsection:integral}
The geodesic  problem on ${S^2}$ has $SO(3)$-symmetry generated by  rotations with respect to each coordinate axis. By Noether's theorem, there are three associated integrals. The argument in Sec \ref{subsection:Moser} implies that the Kepler problem has three integrals associated with three integrals of the geodesic problem.

\;

Consider two vectors
\begin{eqnarray}
\vec{L}  &=& q \times p = (0,0, q_1p_2 - q_2p_1) = (0,0,L), \\
\vec{A}  &=& p \times \vec{L} - \frac{q}{|q|} = \big( p_2L - \frac{q_1}{|q|} ,-p_1 L - \frac{q_2}{|q|},0 \big) = (  A_1,A_2, 0).
\end{eqnarray}
The first vector is called the angular monemtum and the second is the Runge-Lenz vector. For history of the Runge-Lenz vector, for example, see \cite{Gold1}, \cite{Gold2}. 
\begin{figure}[h]
 \centering
 \includegraphics[width=0.6\textwidth, clip]{Rungelenz.pdf}
 \caption{The Runge-Lenz vector: $r =\frac{q}{|q|}$.}
 \label{fig:Rungelenz}
\end{figure}
The properties of these vectors are described in the following.




\begin{Lemma} (i) Three functions ${ L}$, ${A_1}$, and ${A_2}$ are integrals of the Kepler problem.

(ii) ${e^2 = A_1^2 + A_2^2 = 2HL^2 + 1 }$, where ${e}$ is the eccentricity of a Kepler ellipse.

(iii) The Runge-Lenz vector points in the direction of the perihelion of a Kepler ellipse, i.e., the point on the orbit where it is nearest to the origin, see Fig. \ref{fig:Rungelenz}. 
\end{Lemma}

We now apply the switch map and the inverse of the stereographic projection, which are described in Sec. \ref{subsection:Moser}, to these three integrals. We first compute that
\begin{eqnarray*}
L  =  \frac{ \xi_1 }{1-\xi_0 } \big( \eta_2 (1-\xi_0) + \xi_2 \eta_0 \big) - \frac{ \xi_2 }{ 1-\xi_0} \big( \eta_1 ( 1 - \xi_0 ) + \xi_1 \eta_0 \big) = \xi_1 \eta_2 - \xi_2 \eta_ 1 .
\end{eqnarray*}
On the other hand,  in view of ${ \left \langle \xi, \eta \right \rangle  = 0 }$ and ${ | \xi| = |\eta| = 1 }$, we compute that for $\xi_0 \neq 1 $
\begin{eqnarray*}
&&\frac{ ( \xi \times \eta) \times \xi - \eta}{1-\xi_0 } + (\xi \times \eta) \times (1,0 ,0) \\
&&= \bigg( 0, \frac{ -\xi_1 \xi_2 \eta_2 + \xi_2^2 \eta_1}{1-\xi_0 } - \frac{ \eta_1 (1-\xi_0) + \xi_1 \eta_0}{(1-\xi_0)|\eta|}, \frac{ -\xi_1 \xi_2 \eta_1 + \xi_1^2 \eta_2}{1-\xi_0 } - \frac{ \eta_2 (1-\xi_0) + \xi_2 \eta_0}{(1-\xi_0)|\eta|} \bigg) \\
&&=(0, A_1, A_2).
\end{eqnarray*}
Since two vectors $(\xi \times \eta) \times \xi$ and $\eta$ are identical on geodesics with the unit momentum, we conclude that
\begin{eqnarray}
(0, A_1, A_2)  =  (\xi \times \eta) \times (1,0,0) = ( 0, \xi_0 \eta_1 - \xi_1 \eta_0 , \xi_0 \eta_2 - \xi_2 \eta_0 ).
\end{eqnarray}
In conclusion, we have
\begin{eqnarray}
\label{keplerintegrals}
\xi \times \eta = (L, -A_2, A_1) .
\end{eqnarray}
So far, we have excluded the case $\xi_0 =1$, namely the equation (\ref{keplerintegrals}) holds for $\xi_0 \neq 1 $. However, we  can extend two functions $A_1$ and $A_2$ to the collision states by defining them by the same formulas. We have shown that  the symmetries associated with these intergals of the Kepler problem corresponds to the rotational symmetries of the geodesic problem. In particular, the Kepler problem has ${SO(3)}$-symmetry. 

\;

With the previous argument, one can easily find the critical orbits associated with each integral, i.e., a periodic orbit along which the derivative of an integral is parallel to the that of the Hamiltonian. For example, observe that an orbit which is invariant under the rotation with respect to the $\xi_0$-axis, i.e., $L$-symmetry, is a geodesic which lies on the $\xi_1 \xi_2$-plane. In particular, this orbit has zero $\xi_0$-component. By the stereoprojection (\ref{eq:projection}), this orbit maps to a circular orbit. It is well-known that in the Kepler problem,  circular orbits are the critical orbits of the angular momentum $L$. Similar argument  shows that   the critical orbits for ${A_1}$(or $A_2$) are  collision orbits whose semi-major axes lie on the ${q_1}$-axis(or $q_2$-axis).





















