It follows  that on  $l_2$
\begin{eqnarray*}
(\ref{integraleta})_{S'} =  \frac{\pi}{ 2 \sqrt{  -c-1+2\mu }}= (\ref{integraleta})_{S}.
\end{eqnarray*}
On the other hand, for the regions $L$ and $P$, we denote by (\ref{integraleta})$_{\pm}$ the ${\eta}$-integrals for $ (1-2\mu)^2 \geq gc$ and $(1-2\mu)^2 < gc$, respectively. Two integrals are also identical for points $(g,c)$ satisfying $gc= (1-2\mu)^2$ with $c>c_2$. Indeed, if $gc=(1-2\mu)^2$, then we compute that

