\subsection{Rotation function} By the rotation number of a Liouville torus associated with  a point $(g,c)$, we mean the ratio ${R = \big(\tau_{\eta} / \tau_{\xi}\big)(g,c) }$. Since the periods ${\tau_{\eta}}$ and ${\tau_{\xi}}$ depend only on ${g}$ and $c$, the rotation number depends only on a Liouville torus.  An orbit is periodic if and only if its rotation number is rational. In particular, the set of periodic orbits is dense in the set of the whole orbits.  Fixing the rotation number $R$ and varying   $g$ and $c$, the equation $ R = R (g,c) $ defines a smooth family of Liouville tori of the rotation number $R$. If $R = k/l$, where $k,l \in {\mathbb Z}$ are relatively prime, we call such a family of Liouville tori a $T_{k,l}$-torus family. One can easily see that these tori are Morse-Bott nondegenerate. When we consider $R$ as a function of $g$ and $c$, it is called the rotation function. Obviously, two torus families of different rotation numbers never intersect.   If we fix an energy value $c$ and vary the integral $g$, we call $R_c(g) := R (g,c) $ the rotation function on an energy hypersurface $\Sigma_c$. It follows from Lemma \ref{lemma:periodsmonotone} that $R_c$ is strictly increasing in the region $L$. Dullin-Montgomery \cite{syzygy} conjecture that it is strictly decreasing in $S' $-, $S $-, and $P $-regions.  

\begin{Lemma}  
\label{lemma:rotation}
The rotation function for each region is given as follows.
\begin{eqnarray}
&R_{S'}&  = \sqrt[4]{\frac{ 1-gc}{(1-2\mu)^2-gc}}\frac{ K(r_1)}{K(k_1)} \\
