\section{Main argument}

\subsection{The definition of the   Conley-Zehnder index}



We fix some conventions. The symplectic form is given by $ \omega = \sum dp_j \wedge dq_j$ and the Hamiltonian vector field of a Hamiltonian $H$ is defined by $\omega( X_H, \cdot ) = -dH$. 

\;\;

We recall the definition of the Robbin-Salamon index \cite{spectral}. Let  $\psi : [0,T] \rightarrow Sp(2n) $ be a smooth path of symplectic matrices. A point ${t \in [0,T] }$ is called a crossing if $\det(\psi(t) -  I ) =0$. For a crossing $t \in [0,T] $, the crossing form $Q_t$ is defined as the quadratic form 
\begin{eqnarray}
 Q_t(v, v) := \omega( v, \dot{\psi}(t)v), \;\;\;\;\; v \in \text{Eigen}_{1}(\psi(t)) ,
\end{eqnarray}
where $\text{Eigen}_1 (\psi(t)) $ is the eigenspace of $\psi(t)$ to the eigenvalue 1. A crossing $ t \in [a,b]$ is called nondegenerate if the crossing from $Q_t$ is nondegenerate, i.e., the corresponding matrix does not have  an eigenvalue  equal to zero. Assume that the path $\psi$ has only nondegenerate crossings. In particular, they are isolated. Then the Robbin-Salamon index is defined by

If a path $\psi$ has degenerate crossing, we homotope $\psi$ to $\widetilde{\psi}$ with only nondegenerate crossing, where during the homotopy   endpoints are fixed. Robbin-Salamon \cite{spectral} prove that the Robbin-Salamon index is invariant under homotopy with fixing endpoints. Thus, we define
\begin{eqnarray*}
\mu_{\text{RS} }(\psi ) := \mu_{\text{RS}} ( \widetilde{\psi}) .
\end{eqnarray*}

Let $\gamma$ be a  periodic orbit on an energy hypersurface $\Sigma_c$ and $D$ be its spanning disk. We trivialize the contact structure $\xi$ over $D$. Then we obtain a path of symplectic matrices
\begin{eqnarray*}
\psi(t) := \left. \begin{matrix} d{\varphi}_H^t(x) \end{matrix} \right|_{\xi}
\end{eqnarray*}
by linearizing the Hamiltonian flow along $\gamma$ with respect to the chosen trivialization. We define the Conley-Zehnder index of a periodic orbit $\gamma$ by
\begin{eqnarray*}
\mu_{\text{CZ} } (\gamma) := \mu_{\text{RS}}(\psi).
\end{eqnarray*}
Notice that the above definition is well-defined, i.e., it is independent of the choice of the spanning disk and trivialization, since $c_1(T{\mathbb R}^4)=0$.

In this paper, we admit the definition of the Conley-Zehnder index in \cite{HWZ} which is lower-semicontinuous. It is well known that  this definition   coincides with the  above definition via the Robbin-Salamon index   for a nondegenerate periodic orbit, i.e., a periodic orbit $\gamma$ such that $\left. \begin{matrix} d{\varphi}_H^T(x) \end{matrix} \right|_{\xi}$ does not have an eigenvalue equal to 1. Notice that the Robbin-Salamon index is not lower-semicontinuous and two definitions are different for degenerate orbits. 


