\subsection{The Conley-Zehnder indices of  the $T_{k,l}$-type orbits}





Recall that periodic orbits in $T_{k,l}$-torus family are Morse-Bott nondegenerate. It follows from homotopy invariance of the Conley-Zehnder index that any two periodic orbits in the same torus family have the same Conley-Zehnder index. Therefore, to determine the Conley-Zehnder index of torus type orbit it suffices to determine the index of one periodic orbit of each torus family. 

\;\;

We start from the $N$-th iterated interior collision orbit with sufficiently low energy. By the formula (\ref{eq:interior}), its Conley-Zehnder index equals ${ 2N+1}$ and it remains the same until $c=c_{N+1,N}^{\text{int}}$ at which the rotation number is $(N+1)/N$, i.e, $R_{\text{int}}=(N+1)/N$, $\gamma_{\text{int}}^N$ becomes degenerate, and the $T_{N+1,N}$-torus family bifurcates. If we increase an energy slightly more, the Conley-Zehnder index becomes $2N+3$.  Invariance of the local Floer homology gives rise to the fact that every periodic orbit in the $T_{N+1,N}$-torus family has the Conley-Zehnder index $2N+1$. If we increase an energy more, then  at $c=c_{N+2,N}^{\text{int}}$  the $T_{N+2,N}$-torus family bifurcates and by the same argument their Conley-Zehnder indices are equal to $2N+3$. We continue this process until an energy level becomes as close as we want to know to the critical Jacobi energy $c_J$. At each energy level at which the ${T_{k,N}}$-torus family, $k>N$, bifurcates the Conley-Zehnder index of the $N$-covered interior collision orbit increases by 2. Moreover, as before,   via invariance of the local Floer homology and the Morse-Bott nondegeneracy of the torus type orbit we can determine the Conley-Zehnder indices of all the $T_{k,N}$-type orbits. As a result, every ${T_{k,N}}$-type orbit in the region $S'$ or $S$ is of  Conley-Zehnder index $2k-1$.




This completes the proof of Theorem \ref{thm:formula}. \hfill $\square$

\;\;\; 

\subsection{Proof of Theorem \ref{thm:index}} We show that for energies below the critical Jacobi energy,  every contractible periodic orbit is of  Conley-Zehnder index at least 3 and the double-covered exterior collision orbit is the unique contractible  periodic orbit of  Conley-Zehnder index 3 on each connected component of an energy hypersurface.

\;

Albers-Fish-Frauenfelder-van Koert \cite{RKP} prove that in the rotating Kepler problem the circular orbits are contractible if and only if they are evenly-covered. Their argument also holds for the Euler problem, i.e., the interior and the exterior collision orbits are contractible if and only if they are evenly-covered. Then Theorem \ref{thm:formula} shows that contractible interior or exterior collision orbit has  Conley-Zehnder index at least 5 or 3, respectively. Since the covering number of the $T_{k,l}$-torus family is $l$, to be evenly covered, $l \geq 2$. It follows from the fact that $k>l$ in the regions $S'$ and $S$ that $k\geq 3$ and this implies that any contractible regular periodic orbit has   Conley-Zehnder index at least 5. This completes the proof of Theorem \ref{thm:index}. \hfill $\square$








